Title : Hamid Rahmanian
Text : {{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}
'''Hamid Rahmanian''' (born 1968) is a New York–based Iranian multi-disciplinary artist working mostly in cinema, graphic art and shadow  theater. Since the late 1980s, he has combined his love of traditional Persian art forms with modern technology to create new works of art that visually bridge the gaps of East and West.  As a story-teller, his works have focused on people and issues that are rarely covered in the mainstream media, offering audiences new perspectives and intimate glimpses into otherwise little known worlds.

He was educated in [[Tehran]], [[Iran]] where he gained his [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] in [[graphic design]] from [[Tehran University]]. He has worked as a [[graphic designer]] since 1987. In 1992, he received the highest honor and was awarded recognition as the youngest professional designer in [[Iran]].  Rahmanian has continued to work as a graphic designer in the US and has been commissioned to do work for cultural organizations and commercial companies including the United Nations, ''[[GQ]]'' magazine, the [[Lincoln Center]], the [[Tribeca Film Institute]], [[Pacifica Radio]]/[[Democracy Now!]] and the [[Eurasia Foundation]].

== Career ==

Rahmanian moved to the United States and earned a [[Master of Fine Arts]] in [[Computer Animation]] in 1994 from [[Pratt Institute]]. His thesis animation ''The Seventh Day'' (1996) received The First place College Award from the [[Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]], was nominated for a Student Academy Award and was in competition at [[Annecy International Animation Festival]]. In 1996, he was the youngest recipient ever to receive the National Interest Waiver from the U.S. for his outstanding work as an artist. After completing his studies, he was hired by [[Disney]] Feature Animation Company as a Look Development Artist where he worked on ''Tarzan'', ''The Emperor's New Groove'', and ''Dinosaur''. In 1998, Mr. Rahmanian left [[Disney]] and established his own production company, Fictionville Studio.  His first 35&nbsp;mm short film ''An I Within'' (1999), received Kodak's Best Cinematography Award, Best American Short from the LA International Short Film Festival and Special Achievement Award from the [[USA Film Festival]].<ref>{{Citation|title=An I Within - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0204816/awards|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> He went on to make three documentaries. ''Breaking Bread'' (2000) and ''Sir Alfred Of Charles De Gaulle Airport'' (2001)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fictionvillestudio.com/films/alfred/sir-alfred.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-05-02 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106223419/http://fictionvillestudio.com/films/alfred/sir-alfred.html |archivedate=November 6, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> were well received by the media and worldwide audiences.  ''Shahrbanoo'' (2002) first premiered on [[PBS]] station [[WNET]] where it received among the highest ratings for an independently produced documentary<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabfilm.com/item_print.html?itemID=248|title=Shahrbanoo|website=www.arabfilm.com|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> and has been broadcast on networks around the globe.  His first feature length fiction film ''Dame sobh'' (2005) (Persian: دم صبح, ''Dam-e Sobh'', English title: ''[[Day break (2005 film)|Day Break]]'') premiered at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]],<ref>http://www.nooripictures.com/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=68:day-break-dame-sobh&Itemid=68</ref> went on to screen at festivals and theaters all over the world, including the [[Venice Film Festival]] and [[Tribeca Film Festival]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribecafilm.com/filmguide/archive/512d08fc1c7d76e046002add-day-break|title=Day Break {{!}} Tribeca Film Festival|website=Tribeca|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> and won Special Jury Prize at the International Film Festival of Prime in 2006.<ref>http://www.annonaypremierfilm.org/2006/</ref>  ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it, "An impressive debut feature that works like a ticking time bomb".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2005/film/reviews/day-break-2-1200521081/|title=Day Break|last=Koehler|first=Robert|last2=Koehler|first2=Robert|date=2005-10-13|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> ''The Glass House'' (2008 film) a feature-length documentary premiered at the [[Sundance Film Festival]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundance.org/|title=Sundance Institute|website=www.sundance.org|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> and International Documentary Festival  in [[Amsterdam]]<ref>http://www.idfa.nl/industry/tags/project.aspx?id=cc29d602-c45e-4d22-9b2f-80c6dc792816</ref> and was the winner of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe’s ([[OSCE]]) Human Rights Award,<ref>http://newkosovareport.com/200908111880/Culture-and-Sports/kosovo-international-documentary-film-festival-announces-winners.html</ref> among other awards.

Rahmanian's films have consistently sought to combat negative [[stereotypes]] about Iranians, to promote anti-capital punishment laws in the US, and to raise funds and awareness for the plights of disadvantaged women and girls around the world. His films have been televised on international networks, including [[PBS]], Sundance Channel, IFC, [[Channel 4]], [[BBC]], DR2, and [[Al Jazeera]].

In 2003, Rahmanian co-founded and was President (2004–2007) ArteEast, a leading New York-based nonprofit organization dedicated to engaging a growing global audience with the contemporary arts of the Middle East and North Africa.
In 2009, he wrote and illustrated a graphic autobiography entitled ''To Myself With Love'' of which the illustrations were an exhibition called MULTIVERSE at the [[Halsey Institute of Contemporary Art]] in 2011.<ref>http://halsey.cofc.edu/exhibitions/hamid-rahmanian-tanja-softic/</ref> In 2013, Rahmanian illustrated and commissioned a new translation, translated by Dr. Ahmad Sadri, and adaptation of the tenth-century Persian epic poem ''Shahnameh'' by [[Ferdowsi]], entitled ''Shahnameh: The Epic Of The Persian Kings''.  This best-selling, 600 page art book, which according to the [[Wall Street Journal]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/middleeast/2013/05/23/shahnameh-a-persian-masterpiece-still-relevant-today/|title=Shahnameh, a Persian Masterpiece, Still Relevant Today|last=Fassihi|first=Farnaz|date=2013-05-23|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> is a "Masterpiece," published by The Quantuck Lane Press and distributed by [[W. W. Norton & Company]].  The limited edition version of the book was exhibited at the [[Library of Congress]] in 2014 as part of their "1000 years of the Persian Book" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.loc.gov/today/cyberlc/feature_wdesc.php?rec=7179|title=A Thousand Years of the Persian Book: A Curator's Tour Webcast {{!}} Library of Congress|website=www.loc.gov|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> exhibition.

Rahmanian has been awarded a 2014 John Simon [[Guggenheim Fellow]] Award.<ref>http://www.gf.org/fellows/17658-hamid-rahmanian</ref>

Rahmanian began experimenting with shadow theater techniques in 2014.  He created a short 20-minute shadow play with overhead projectors titled ''Zahhak: The Legend of the Serpent King'', based on a fable from the Shahnameh.  It premiered at the [[Asia Society]] in New York City and later on the [[Brooklyn Academy of Music]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bam.org/kids/2017/zahhak-legend-of-the-serpent-king|title=Zahhak: Legend of the Serpent King|website=BAM.org|access-date=2017-01-05}}</ref> and the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian Institute]]/Freer Sackler Museum. 

In 2016, Rahmanian created, designed and directed the stage production of ''Feathers of Fire'', an adaption of the Persian love story of [[Zāl|Zaul]] and [[Rudabeh]] from the [[Shahnameh]].   This "jaw-dropping"<ref>{{Citation|title='Feathers of Fire': Spectacular Shadow Play|url=https://www.kcet.org/shows/socal-connected/feathers-of-fire-spectacular-shadow-play|accessdate=2017-01-05}}</ref> live animation-like shadow play incorporated shadow casters, puppets, digitally projected animation and music to create a "feast for the senses"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unima-usa.org/pi-40-selection/?rq=feathers%20of%20fire|title=PI 40 Selection|website=UNIMA-USA|access-date=2017-01-05}}</ref> according to Puppetry International Magazine.  [[Le Figaro]] called it "astonishing and magical"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/sortir-paris/2018/12/11/30004-20181211ARTFIG00251-shahname-une-epopee-persane-au-quai-branly.php|title=Shâhnâmé, une épopée persane au musée du quai Branly|date=2018-12-11|website=FIGARO|access-date=2019-04-11}}</ref> and NYC Theater Review exclaimed that it was a "masterpiece"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatrereview.nyc/latest/feathers-of-fire-a-review|title=The Latest|website=TRNYC|language=en|access-date=2019-04-11}}</ref>.  The play premiered at the [[Brooklyn Academy of Music]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bam.org/kids/2016/feathers-of-fire-a-persian-epic|title=Feathers of Fire: A Persian Epic|website=BAM.org|access-date=2017-01-05}}</ref>. It played at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] and toured around the world between 2016 and 2018. That same year, he was commissioned by the [[Alexander S. Onassis Foundation|Onassis Foundation]] to write and direct a shadow play based the Greek tragedy of [[Antigone]], called ''Mina's Dream''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.onassisfestivalny.org/minas-dream/|title=Mina’s Dream|newspaper=Onassis Festival NY|access-date=2017-01-05}}</ref>

In 2017, he released an immersive audiobook version of Shahnameh: The Epic of the Persian Kings with an introduction by [[Francis Ford Coppola|Frances Ford Coppola]].  In 2018, Rahmanian released the pop up book [http://www.kingorama.com/shahnameh-zahhak-the-legend-of-the-serpent-king Zahhak: The Legend of the Serpent King] through [[Fantagraphics Books]]. The book which [[Le Monde]] called "simply breathtaking"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2019/04/11/hundreds-witness-veteran-shoot-and-kill-himself-in-va-waiting-room/|title=Hundreds witness veteran shoot and kill himself in VA waiting room|last=Simkins|first=J. D.|date=2019-04-12|website=Military Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> won the 2018 Meggendorfer Prize for the Best Pop Up Book.  The French publication La Croix called it "magnificent"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.la-croix.com/Journal/Selection-livres-2017-12-13-1100898994|title=Sélection livres|date=2017-12-13|access-date=2019-04-11|language=fr-FR|issn=0242-6056}}</ref> and the New York Journal of Books said it was a "book that demands respect."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyjournalofbooks.com/book-review/zahhak|title=a book review by Annette Lapointe: Zahhak: The Legend of the Serpent King (A Pop-Up Book)|website=www.nyjournalofbooks.com|access-date=2019-04-11}}</ref> The book was published in French and English.

In 2019, Rahmanian collaborated with [[Kayhan Kalhor|Keyhan Kalhor]] and the [[The Silk Road Ensemble|Silk Road Ensemble]] on their project, Heroes Take Their Stand, where he created a 23-minute animation about the life of the Persian hero Siavosh from Shahnameh. 

== Personal life ==

Rahmanian is married to Melissa Hibbard, his creative partner, a photographer and a filmmaker, with whom he has a daughter Sophie.

